  "text": "## HTTP Health Check Endpoint Comparison Across Go Projects\n\n### Kubernetes\n**Endpoints:** `/healthz`, `/readyz`, `/livez`\n\nKubernetes provides a comprehensive health checking framework through the apiserver package. The main implementation is in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz/healthz.go`, which defines a pluggable `HealthChecker` interface. The registration functions `InstallHandler()`, `InstallReadyzHandler()`, and `InstallLivezHandler()` register handlers on the HTTP mux at lines 171, 179, and 187 respectively.\n\nThe health check system supports:\n- **Default checks:** `PingHealthz` (always passes), `LogHealthz` (ensures logging isn't blocked), and `informerSync` (checks if informers have synced)\n- **Shutdown check:** Fails when graceful shutdown is initiated\n- **Custom checks:** Can be added via the `HealthChecker` interface\n- **Features:** Query parameter support for excluding checks (`?exclude=check1,check2`), verbose output (`?verbose=1`), and grouped checks\n\nIn `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz.go`, the `GenericAPIServer` provides methods to add checks:\n- `AddBootSequenceHealthChecks()` - Adds checks to all three endpoints with a grace period for livez\n- `AddReadyzChecks()` - Adds checks to the readiness endpoint\n- `AddLivezChecks()` - Adds checks to the liveness endpoint\n\nThe endpoints are installed in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/genericapiserver.go` at lines 459-468. The `/healthz` and `/livez` endpoints are installed early, while `/readyz` includes a shutdown check to ensure requests aren't routed to the server during graceful shutdown.\n\n### Grafana\n**Endpoints:** `/livez`, `/readyz`, `/healthz`\n\nGrafana uses a simpler health checking mechanism based on atomic state signaling. The core implementation is in `pkg/server/health.go`, which defines a `HealthNotifier` struct using `atomic.Bool` to track readiness state.\n\nThe health endpoint implementation is straightforward:\n- **`LivezHandler()`** - Always returns HTTP 200 OK (simple liveness check at line 38-42)\n- **`ReadyzHandler(h *HealthNotifier)`** - Returns HTTP 200 OK if `h.IsReady()` is true, otherwise returns HTTP 503 Service Unavailable (lines 47-56)\n- **`RegisterHealthEndpoints(router *mux.Router, h *HealthNotifier)`** - Registers both endpoints on the provided router (lines 61-63)\n\nIn `pkg/api/http_server.go` at line 758, there's additional handling for the `/healthz` endpoint that excludes it from domain enforcement checks. The endpoints are registered in `pkg/server/instrumentation_service.go` at line 65 where `RegisterHealthEndpoints()` is called with the health notifier.\n\nGrafana's approach is minimal and relies on operators signaling readiness via `HealthNotifier.SetReady()` and `HealthNotifier.SetNotReady()` methods.\n\n### Prometheus\n**Endpoints:** `/-/healthy`, `/-/ready`\n\nPrometheus provides health and readiness endpoints with a state machine approach. The implementation is in `web/web.go` at lines 591-604. Unlike the other projects, Prometheus uses the `/-/` prefix (reserved management APIs) rather than the standard Kubernetes health check paths.\n\nThe health endpoint design:\n- **`/-/healthy` endpoint** (lines 591-596) - Always returns HTTP 200 OK with message \"{AppName} is Healthy.\\n\". Supports both GET and HEAD methods.\n- **`/-/ready` endpoint** (lines 598-603) - Returns HTTP 200 OK only when the server's `ready` status is set to `Ready`. Otherwise returns HTTP 503 Service Unavailable.\n\nThe `ready` field in the `Handler` struct (line 247) is an `atomic.Uint32` that stores a `ReadyStatus` enum value. The `testReady()` method (lines 659-676) wraps handlers to enforce readiness checks:\n- `Ready` status: Handler executes normally\n- `NotReady` status: Returns HTTP 503 with message \"Service Unavailable\"\n- `Stopping` status: Returns HTTP 503 with X-Prometheus-Stopping header set to \"true\"\n- Default: Returns HTTP 500 with message \"Unknown state\"\n\nPrometheus also supports both GET and HEAD methods for these endpoints as documented in `docs/management_api.md`, which states that these endpoints facilitate automation and integration with container orchestration systems.\n\n### Key Differences Summary\n\n1. **Path naming:** Kubernetes uses `/healthz`, `/livez`, `/readyz`; Grafana uses `/livez`, `/readyz`, `/healthz`; Prometheus uses `/-/healthy`, `/-/ready`\n2. **Checks complexity:** Kubernetes has the most sophisticated check system with pluggable checkers and grouping; Grafana uses simple atomic state; Prometheus uses a state machine with multiple states\n3. **Liveness vs Readiness:** Kubernetes provides separate liveness and readiness endpoints with different grace periods; Grafana and Prometheus keep them separate but simpler\n4. **Dependencies checked:** Kubernetes checks informers and logging; Grafana checks operator initialization state; Prometheus checks server ready state\n5. **Graceful shutdown:** Kubernetes and Prometheus explicitly handle shutdown state; Grafana handles this via readiness flag"
